The interior was pretty industrial, but there were lots of little couches, chairs and tables to sit at. Also, there was a friendly dog who was wandering around, greeting customers. 

Good to know that this place is in my neighborhood and that it offers such a nice experience. I'll definitely be back!

What a cool place!  It's a "nano" brewery or something like that ... small batches of locally brewed beer, with a menu that changes at least weekly.  Belly up to their bar and you can taste as many beers as you wish for free.  My husband and I have very different tastes in beers, and I love being able to choose our favorite styles.  Another great local business to support.

Some of the best craft beer in the city and only 8 minutes from my house.  Located next to Great Fermentations (beer making supply store), Bier is awesome on Saturdays where pints are sometimes sold.  It's fun hanging out while beer tour buses come and go unloading enthusiastic beer connoisseurs.

Definitely don't come here without the intention of staying for a couple of hours - this place has won awards for their beer but definitely not the service. We waited for about 20 minutes without anyone in front of us and had 1 sample. We really wanted to buy a couple of growlers for a cookout but I guess we'll just have to stick with buying cans at other retailers.

Awesome beer, awesome staff, awesome atmosphere.

I first stopped into Bier Brewery two days ago after learning of them on Beer Advocate. I was fortunate enough to show up when they weren't too busy and was able to chat with Ben and Jerry, two personable and engaging staff behind the bar, and a few other friendly customers. Bier's line-up tends to be on the less bitter side, which makes me extremely happy. Of the seven or eight beers I tasted, most ranged from 10-20 IBUs (International Bittering Units scale, a measurement of a beer's bitterness, with 0 as the lowest possible). Only one rated at 50 or above, and even that tasted delicious!

When I visited a couple days ago, I picked up a growler of Weizengoot, my favorite of the seven. It had an enticing deep-orange hue and looked simply fantastic. The first sip tasted faintly like Blue Moon, but the finish felt closer to Hoegaarden -- an excellent combination, yet still wonderfully unique. Since I had to share, the growler lasted less than an hour! I stopped into Bier again this afternoon -- Sunday growler sales in Indiana are a beautiful thing! -- but was mildly disappointed to discover  that Bier had already sold out of the Goot. Blast! 

Instead, I chose my second favorite -- Chamomille Wheat. Another delicious wheat beer, somehow light-tasting yet full-bodied? Yes, please. The growler is now nearly empty... and I didn't have to share this time!

While the prices ($12-14 for a fill) are just a touch high (I'm spoiled by $6-9 fills), they're well worth it for such fantastic beer -- and for supporting such a great, up-and-coming small business. They're such relative newcomers, their beer is only sold on the premises -- you can't buy it in any bars or stores, but I imagine that will quickly change once word gets out and they're able to ramp up production.

In short, I can't wait to go back to Bier. Next time, I'll be bringing two or three growlers with me!
These guys are artists! Their beer selection and relaxed environment is always great. Love this place!

Soooo I don't really have a penchant for beer drinking -- wino here, but when I do drink beer, I prefer local craft options.  theCityMoms did an event here in September and this was a perfect location!  I loved the mid-town accessibility and there is always plenty of parking.  It's cozy and intimate inside with an approachable bar, showing off the latest brews.  The staff was awesome and accommodating for the moms who needed to come in and warm up with a brew or a place to sit.  I had a blond wheat which I don't think is on their current rotating list but it was delicious.  I thought the price was on point as well and not too expensive.  They do growler fills and offer seasonal choices throughout the year.  Great place to meet up with friends new and old.  Making beer wishes and dreams come true - always something new to try.

Best beer and brewery in indy. Sadly loses huge points for lack luster service. I've been numerous times and they are quick to get rid of you. Met one of their brewers once and the guy was awesome and showed me a lot. This place would be the best if the servers were happier and better at customer service.

Ok, so love that there was a dog to greet us upon entry! So friendly! We went up to bar and the lady was very informative. She gave everyone a sample of every beer they had on tap. I. didn't get any since I was driving. I tasted some of my husband's though and really only liked two of them. You can buy "bullets" which is 32oz bottles as carry out, but you couldn't drink there otherwise. I found it strange, but it is just a tasting room. They did have some pretty creative names for their beers that were for next week. Makes me want to go back just to try them!

Another cool brewery tap room in Indy. The location is pretty easy to get to as long as it isn't rush hour, and they have plenty of parking in the parking lot for the strip mall of businesses that they are set up in. There is quite a bit of outdoor seating in a patio area in front of the business, and a lot more seating inside that is composed of some second-hand mismatched furniture (including a few couches). Ordering is done at their bar that has a large chalkboard behind it with the available beers on tap.
 
It's a fairly busy interior with lots of stuff hanging everywhere, including a significant amount of awards that they have won for their beers. There are also lots of branded items that you can buy. They have 6-packs of their canned beer already cold that you can purchase to-go, or you can make a build your own 6 pack. You can also fill growlers here. The beers from this brewery are always done exceptionally well for the style, but they also lack some of the more unique beers that a lot of other breweries like to make. They have 8 or 9 beers on tap at any time, and they usually cover a decent spectrum of beer styles. This is definitely a brewery that isn't going to put out anything that isn't done well.

They have quite a few unique events here that can be easily found on their website, including a night especially for dogs, live music, and even a euchre night. Wednesday is their pint night with the fantastic offering of $4 pints. There was a food truck here the last time I visited, but I think that is only a once a week occasion (but don't quote me on that). They did have a few snack items available if needed to buy something to tide you over while drinking. 

I don't make it here very often since it requires a drive to get here, but it is definitely a stop I would make if I was going to be in the area. If you like great beer in a relaxed atmosphere, this is definitely your place. Additionally, and this may be a little judgmental of me, but the crowd here seems to be a little more "normal" than some other breweries. It's not full of regulars that feel like they have priority in the place and there are far less hipsters than some of the downtown breweries pull in. It's a nice social place to come with some friends to enjoy a few beers no matter what demographic you belong to.

This is the best new brewery in the city. The beers are always stellar. The staff is friendly. There are comfy chairs to sit in and a new dartboard too. Best of all is that they're dog friendly. I'm a huge fan of Bier. Come taste their awesomeness.

Once I walked in from the patio on the north side of the building, the first thing I noticed was a wall loaded with awards for the prize winning ales that this place has won at the Indiana Brewers Cup.  Since 2012, it seems Bier Brewery has had prize winners.  So the bar is set pretty high for your drinking experience.

I have had a number of their canned beverages around town.  They make a variety of brews including Special K (kolsch), Weizengoot (Hefewizen), and PDG ("Pretty Darn Good" American pale).  I have enjoyed them all!

The interior is dim and filled with assorted tables, chairs, and a lounge area.  The restrooms have been designated as Stouts and Blondes, so I guess that is understood to be gender neutral (I hope so since I am neither stout, at least not yet, or blonde!)

In the back corner is the counter/tap area with a list of the current taps artistically displayed on the chalkboard.  One thing I liked was that the counter has several laminated flip folders describing each of the featured brews.  I am still learning about craft beers, so I enjoy reading the details of each brew when available.

My only negative was that the brewery doesn't have flights of beer to sample.  Instead, they give free samples in small plastic cups.  In fact, you can try everything they have on tap!  But I found the samples too small (they said 3 oz, but they actually were only partly filled so about the size of a shot) to be able to distinguish the uniqueness of each brew, especially if you don't get a glass of water to clear the taste of the previous sample.  Of the four samples I tried, only the seasonal pumpkin ale stood out and the spices overwhelmed the beer and pumpkin flavors.    For me, I would prefer a legitimate four or five ounce sample to see how the flavors hold up to appreciate the nuance of each selection.  That's why I like the flights.  I don't want to buy a whole pint and find out that I may not like how the taste develops.  

I know the brewery makes good beer, so even though I was disappointed with my visit to the brewery/taproom, I don't need to see the awards to know this place will continue on the right path.  I simply wish they would add the option of flights like so many of the other breweries around town.

Review #390
Bier brews really fantastic beer. It's pretty annoying though that we can only get pints on Fridays and Saturdays. What if I want Bier Beer on Monday night (from Bier)?

This place is awesome! I had heard a lot about this place and people told me I needed to check it out and they were right. First things first, this is a BREWERY, no they don't have food, but they have food trucks stop by often. No they are not a big coorporate chain, they are a local start up! This place is about beer and only beer the way it should be! Not only are they brewing some delicious beer but the place is awesome too. It sits in basically a little strip or warehouse. Brewing in the back, tap room in the front. Reminded me of a lot of the little breweries and how they start up in Denver. Very cozy social vibe. Think living room with couches and side tables, chairs and a few high table tops. If you are a fan of the true craft of beer then this place won't let you down. For those of you that homebrew, Great Fermentations homebrew supply is just 50 feet away! I will be bringing the growlers back soon! Cheers!
Really good German-style loggers and ales. Nice variety and large number of taps. Very friendly bartenders too!

Darren makes great beer.  But not enough of it.  That's the -only- reason I'm not giving them five stars.  His beer is SO good that unless you get there the DAY it's released, it sells out. ...Good for them, but not so good for me!  But this speaks well of their choice between quality and profit.  I'm sure they'll ramp up production as they see fit, and we can always count on a superior product, as long as we're "the early bird."

My favorite Indianapolis beers are Bier's. If you're going for the beer, you will not be disappointed. The folks behind the counter will supply you with free samples of whatever you want to taste. Pints are not sold here. So, bring your growler or bullet and plan to fill up. 

You can stand around the bar to have your samples or you can mosey over to the couches or tables. There's a record player too. 

If you're eyeballing that $54 insulated steel growler and wondering "Does it actually work?" I can confirm that it does. We have kept beer (unopened) in the fridge for a month, transported the beer 4 hours without a cooler, and opened the growler to find perfect and COLD beer inside. 

I hope they strike a deal with nearby Fancy Fortune Cookies to offer cookie snacks.

I wanted to update my review because I stopped in last night, and really had a great experience. The staff was really friendly, and allowed me to taste ALL of their beer (I guess they will do this as long as they aren't too busy). I'm glad I was able to sample all of them, because I found a few varieties that I loved.

They didn't have DFG (which is my one of my favorite beers available at Bier and also just overall in Indy), but they did have an IPA I hadn't tried before called Bubonic Chronic. It was pretty tasty and I drank a pint to kill some time before dinner. I also loved their Pumpkin Porter and Pumpkin Ale, and brought home a bullet of the Pumpkin Ale to go.

They had live music, and a chill vibe. Most of the people in the tap room were between 30 - 50 years old, which lends a different atmosphere to some of the other breweries in Indy.

I know this is a favorite brewery amoung the beer lovers out there, but let me just say from a lady who usually sticks to her corona lights - this is the best beer I have ever had!  I think I finally understand why there are so many beer lovers out there.  Even if you aren't a beer drinker, you will love this beer.
Awesome craft beers! Their Pumpkin Beer release party was a blast. My favorite beer is the Weizengoot.
Good ambience and Friendly staff that will give you plenty of samples until you find something you like.

Great Beer! My biggest problem with this brewery is that it is a sample and growler fill station most of the time. I was told you can only get a pint and hang out on Saturdays which makes this a brewery I am less likely to patronize. The staff is friendly and the beer is amazing (what I have had of it) but what is a brewery without being able to sit down, have a pint and be apart of a community?

PUPPIES!  I kinda freaked out on a patron's adorable dog-- Janie.  I like that they allow dogs inside and that it has the feel of a family den.  Staff is knowledgeable and told me they are zero waste (except for when they have food services), on which I commend them (golf clap).  We stayed for only a couple of beers, but I could see settling in for quite a while at this place.

Beer, bier, bejau, birra. No matter how you say it, beer is good and these guys are good at making it. 

Located two doors down from great fermentations, they offer a good selection of small batch beers.

Their tiny batches allow them to have a little more fun with the beer. Just because you've had a beer (example: cream ale) somewhere else, doesn't mean it will be the same here. 

Their tasting line changes weekly, and upcoming beers are listed at the left of the board. They have handy little flashcards about their beers on the counter, so if they are busy enough that you don't get a full explanation form the brewer, you can still learn about the beer from the card. 

They have a big, inviting tap room and seem to be more focused on making sure you get to try the beer and learn about what you are drinking rather than getting as many people through as they can. That's not to say that you will be left waiting in line for a taste. Everyone seems to get plenty of attention and if you wait for a taste at all, it won't be a long wait.

What a cool brewery in the middle of an industrial area turned into a semi-art area.  The brews were and are delicious and the atmosphere is laid back. The staff were knowledgable, friendly and passionate about what they were offering.  I strolled in on a Saturday afternoon to check it out and left with a growler full of goods and a new sweatshirt!  I love their merchandise because their logo is really neat and the prices are very reasonable.  Who doesn't want to rep local breweries?!

I don't give 5 stars lightly. Bier is a world-class brewery, one of the best in Indy, and one of the three that I go to the most (along with Union and Black Acre). Here are the reasons why their beer is great:

* High quality and consistency (gotta have this, of course).

* Distinctive house style. Bier beer is instantly recognizable. Their beer has a very fresh, lucid, clear, clean taste with all of the flavors distinct. Good balance, and the flavors pop in a certain way that is hard to describe. Try it and you'll see what I mean.

* A solid niche. Although Bier can do hoppy very well (their PDG pale ale is distinctive and a real favorite), that's not their focus. They do lagers, wheat beers, and less-hoppy ales with great skill, and they make them exciting and interesting as well. Yesterday I sampled their International Exchange lager and Good Pils (humble name, this!), and both were subtly incredible.

Beyond the beer, there are some other great reasons to visit:

* Friendly staff with a great vibe. They clearly are enjoying their work and are fans of their own brewery.

* Great, comfortable space. It's inviting and easygoing.

* Dogs welcome inside!

* They don't do flights, but you can sample all of the beers at the counter.

* Lots of live music and activities.

If you are a beer nut, Bier definitely belongs high on your list to try. If you are looking for a good place to hang out with friends and have a sip of brew that will please connoisseurs and average drinkers alike, I do believe you will be pleased.

Attended a comedy night last weekend and they were all hilarious, I had tears in my eyes at one point! I tried a couple of different beers before making my selection, and the bartender was very knowledgeable and helpful. I love that they are dog friendly and I can't wait to come back and bring my dog!! I would definitely suggest the comedy nights or any event they host, it was a great night!

Such a cool microbrewery and tap room.  Bier is located in an unassuming strip mall on 65th St. just west of Binford.

The tap room is huge, and the tasting bar is all the way in the back.  Unfortunately (or fortunately depending on your point-of-view) the bar is tiny and can only accomodate about 10 people at a time.  This is good in a way because you get personalized attention from whoever is pouring your beers.  They will go out of their way to describe each beer they have on tap.   And describe they must because they usually have a prodigious number available at the time.  I think they had at least 10 the last time I was there.

They have no "house beers", meaning that if you find one you especially enjoy, you better fill a growler or two because it may not be available the next time you come.  They do try to have certain styles available all the time (i.e. lager, ale, etc.)

Great place, great beer.  Not much to the front, public area, but it's comfy.  A good number of beers always on tap, but they change every week.  Bier doesn't have a constant beer like Sun Light/Osiris.  Lighter beers on the right and stronger/bitter beers on the right (hope I remembered that correctly).  Passionate owner and co-workers (family).
Great beer and phenomenal people. Highly recommended!

Very good beer.  My friends and I enjoyed ourselves.  I especially like the banana and cloves beer.  SWEET and TASTY.

In the table was a bowl of fortune cookies.  The fortunes were hilarious.  Clearly the owners of Bier put a lot of thought into this.  I apologize for my group eating the entire bowl of cookies.  The fortunes were clever, funny - one in particular made my group totally lose it.

Thanks for the good time.

We are obsessed with this brewery! The staff is friendly and the beer is GREAT. This was one of our stops on our Indy Brew Bus tour and probably one of our favorites. They have some of their staple beers, but also have seasonal ones too. Check their Facebook page for special events too!

Let me start by saying that I am THRILLED that this brewery is so close to my house! The bier is done so well that it is hard to believe 3 young men are creating sure yummy goodness. But then again.... it's really not...
I have never been much of a fan of cream stouts or ale, so imagine my surprise when I walked out with a growler of one! We also brought home a growler of Belgian Dubbel, so very easy to drink that I am not sure it will make it past this evening. My other favorites were the Blond and the oatmeal stout. I hope they will be available when I return for my next refill.

The atmosphere here is laid back and friendly, the bier talk is great and the people pouring the bier are also those who make it, so ask questions.
Comfy sofas are available to relax in, and vinyl records are abundant, just pick what you would like to hear and pop it on the record player! I really like that touch! This is a dog friendly place and the sweet mascot will greet you when you walk in.
The website will keep you up to date on what is on tap, so check before you go if you are the picky type.... Adventurous type only need to check the hours!
Cheers!

I always really enjoy the beers at Bier. They are well crafted and a good variety of styles are typically available. I must admit I miss the days when you could sample everything but I understand. I suggest you tag team your three samples so you can try more of the deliciousness. Then buy a pint (if you can, depending on the day) or at the very least a bullet. Be aware, they'll probably sell out of everything by Sunday.

My wife and I contacted Bier Brewery about two weeks prior to our wedding in hopes of obtaining about fifteen cases of their delicious beers for our big day.  I was connect with Ryan who worked quickly to help us get everything together in a very short period of time.  To make things easier for us since we were coming from out of state, they allowed us to pay over the phone at an incredible price point for craft beer and they also allowed a friend of ours to pick up the beer outside of their normal operating hours.  We could not have been happier with the service from Ryan and the rest of the Bier Brewery staff.  Thanks Bier Brewery for helping make our big day even better!!!

This Brewery is awsome.
Taste is All !!

Tap will often change.
This has also become a pleasure to go to Tap room.

There is an amazing kind Beer.
I want the future to taste all of the beer here !!

I like very much !!

The beer was as good as any other small brewery in town and I liked the atmosphere of their tap room. I was also impressed with the attentiveness of one of the staff that served my samples, answered my questions and filled my growlers. 

I was not impressed with another of the staff I talked to and asked about getting a keg filled. I was told they could, but it would be expensive because they didn't really have to--they would sell all their beer anyway. I would never tell one of my customers something is expensive because it's something I don't HAVE to do for them. After having this conversation, seeing their slogan, Come Taste Our Awesomeness, and other information on their website, I'm left with a bad taste in my mouth--arrogance.

11/17/11: In respone to Darren C.:
You didn't tell me you wouldn't fill my keg for sanitation reasons...you told me you wouldn't because "We don't have to, we will sell [all our beer] anyway." I'm a homebrewer and am aware of the importance of sanitation--I have had more than my share of spoiled batches. I would have been fine with that reason or just "No, we don't fill kegs."

Went here to enhance my local beer culture and might I say, these guys have it figured out. They focus on the craft of the beer and it shows. My wife and I tried all of their selection and they were all terrific! The flavor of each is unique and complex. It is not an overwhelming wall of flavor, but deep and rich. 

I wish I was still in the area so I could give them my money.

Looking forward to coming back to you guys and filling all 4 of my growlers!

Cozy little spot with good beer. We went on a Friday and there was live music which was great, a little loud for the space, but not out of control. I wish they had longer hours as there have been several times I wanted to go and they aren't open, but the hours are easy to find. I will definitely be back.

It is my opinion that Bier Brewery is one of the finest (if not THE finest) breweries in Indianapolis.  In a city that is flooded with breweries trying to make their mark, I can always count on a Bier brew to be delicious.  As much as I enjoy downing a pint (or three) of their sudsy goodness at a local bar, it surprises me that it took me so long to make my way to their Tap Room.  Honestly I only stopped by because I was making a trip to their neighbor Great Fermentations and decided to head inside on a recent Friday night.

Their tap room is set up for groups of nearly any reasonable size.  Couples will find seating as easily as groups of 8.  They have several tables with mismatched chairs and couches.  In the corner they even have a spot for some live music which we got to enjoy during our visit.  

Head to the back right corner and tell the workers if you've never been, because they will be happy to help you sample and select a good brew.  Beers are served in plastic cups, which I think could definitely be upgraded at some point since it felt a little cheap to me (but hey, no dishes to wash!).  Follow the staff recommendations, because they want to make you happy and provide you with something new!

All in all I have to say that I would come back again!  One thing that was a tad disappointing is the turnaround time for a keg.  There are some places in Indy that can have kegs waiting and can provide them the same day you call, but Bier asked for 48 hours to fill an order.  We decided to go elsewhere simply because they could fill our order faster.

We recently entered a dish in a local cooking competition that featured the Fuggit Stout from Bier Brewery as one of the ingredients. We won the contest and the $500 prize that came along with it. 

Thanks, Bier!
Awesome and perfect!! Great staff and superb beir!!Having a great evening with Jeff & Tammy and Joshua & Mitch  !!!!!
Really good beer. I like the idea they have comfy coaches so you can chill and have a beer.

I was here for the Brews & Boutiques event put on by Girls Pint Out and CityMoms. I loved the atmosphere in the tap room. The staff were friendly and helpful and of course the beer was fantastic. I had the PDR, stands for Pretty Damn Good, and it was exactly that!

Also a note on the event, it was a fun time for sure. A lot of great fashion trucks came out: Pretty Boho, Genie's Closet, retro 101, Bark Truck, Bizzy's Boutique and there was one more I forget the name of. Scratch food truck showed up to feed everyone. 

Money well spent on a couple unique clothing pieces and great beer!
Decent beer, atmosphere is pretty chill, sometime too quite. Love that it's pet friendly inside!

These guys are working their ass off trying to keep up with demand.  Indy should feel real lucky to have this little gem.  This is a tasting room only, samples and growler fills only.  This is as fresh as beer as your gonna get, hands down.  

Darren and crew, you fuckin rock!

I am truly a fan.  I have known Darren since he worked at the other end of the strip mall at Great Fermentations.  Now he has his own pico-brewery (I am not even sure it would qualify as a nano-brewery with his batch sizes, lol) yet he still loves talking about brewing with other homebrewers.  He still basically is one, his equipment just got a little bigger.  Darren and his crew have McGyvered the entire place.  He built the brewstand he uses, he built his own keg washer, he even engineered and built his own cooler rooms that you see.  The man has truly built the place from the ground up and considered every detail.

When I say he is a pico-brewer, I do not mean that disparagingly.  His super small batches of beer allow him to do things that most other brewers cannot due to scale.  He can control every detail.  He can make sure that everything that goes in is top quality.  His attention to detail and high level of skill shows through in his brews.  Even beer styles that I do not like I can try there and think "Not my thing, but DAMN it is made well!"

Those small batches show his skill in other ways.  When you have tiny batches such as his, tiny errors show through in huge ways.  Multi-thousan gallon batches can hide errors.  When you brew less than a 100 gallons at a time even a few grams on some ingredients can make drastic changes.  The fact that he can consistently brew great beer in small quantities shows the skill of the brewers at Bier Brewery.

And seriously, who doesn't love walking into a place and being greeted by a dog??  :)

BEST local beer in Indy!
This quaint family-owned joint has quite a range of options on the ever changing Bier Board. They are dog-friendly & HUGE supporters of the Indy Fuel. Although they don't offer food, you are welcome to bring your own & hang out on the comfy couches or around a table with friends. Wednesday night's are $4 Pint night & Thursdays are Euchre night. Bring your own growler or buy one of their own with their clever design, but trust, you will want to take home some of this liquid gold.

This brewery is our favorite in Indy! They always have several beers that I like, and I'm pretty picky. The atmosphere is neat and eclectic, too. 

Their artwork on the chalkboard is always amazing, and I spend half my time looking at it. 

Giving it 4 stars out of 5 because the staff is friendly, but sometimes in their own little world.

Awesome spot! They have at least 9 rotating taps at any given time. The don't do flights but give as many free samples as you want in order for you to try and find something you may like. I had been told their ESB was one of the best around and they were right. It's delicious! This place is a must!!

The beer here is simply phenomenal. The rotating selection makes it a weekly event that you look forward to- I have never been disappointed with anything I have tried. Even things you don't care for are done so well that you end up liking them here. Jerry is really helpful, they have great customer relations, and there is always a crowd. The only downside is the amount that they can brew- get there early. They sell out by Sunday almost every week and aren't yet on tap anywhere (much to my dismay). But this place is amazing. The Belgium Blonde and any of their dark brews are a tongue-pleasing experience.

I don't always like their beers, mainly because I'm not necessarily a fan of all the styles of beer that they brew here, but I do recognize that this place has the best execution of the things they brew. In other words, while I may not like everything they serve, they do it all well. 

Some of my favorites here include their coffee porter and their pumpkin ale (the best pumpkin offering in the city). I recently also had their pumpkin porter which was amazing.

I really like their space as well, but I find the tasting bar to be too small and getting served (or even bellying up to the bar) can sometimes be a challenge. It's also disappointing that you can't always get a pint of beer here. That only happens when there's a food truck out front. I'd really love to have a pint and sit in the taproom, but more often than not, the space goes unused.

Plastic cups. I paid $5 to drink out of a plastic cup, indoors. Growler prices are too high as well. The beers are an 8/10 and I'd probably enjoy it from the many other bars and taverns that serve it on tap throughout Indianapolis, but the service at the Bier Brewery is unenthusiastic. The two times I have come in I was treated as a burden.

WOW!  Their beer is so amazing that I'm not sure I can rave enough about it!  Lately I've been getting bored with beer (I know, crazy), but the Bier Brewery revived my love of beer.  The have about 8 rotating beer (err.. bier) taps, and you can sample all of them.  My favorites were the Belgium Triple, Mint Chocolate Stout, and Winter Porter.  They also had a Wheat, Red, and an IPA, which were very good.  All of the beers were perfectly balanced with subtle but delicious and interesting flavor. Most beers are $12 per growler, $15 for a few with a higher alcohol content.  Go there.  Now.  Or don't and leave more for me!

As a beer enthusiast, Bier has established a great atmosphere, helpful staff, and delicious beer! My first adventure to Bier included multiple tastings of their rotated brews and a friendly and helpful staff. (I apologize for not remembering the names of the individuals but thank you for the growler box and your hospitality.)

With beer being my favorite thing in the world, they also have number two: a record player. If you want to sample some great beer, lounge with some friends, and get a growler to go, Bier is a great place to go. I love that they mainly just provided samples and continue to capture the community feel to their establishment. Thank you for coming to the neighborhood.

Ambiance is industrial chic, service can be a bit lacking on Fridays (they really need a bigger bar area and more staff) but if you go in there on a Wednesday expect to have a good conversation about beer. Good variety they tend to have 6 to 8 beers for sampling at all times. The variety goes from wheat beers up to some very nice porters and beyond.  They don't have any food but if your lucky there might be a food truck there on a Friday. The prices are kind of high from 12-17 dollars for a growler but they do sell half growlers that they fill for half price. Overall I'm glad to have this brewery in Indy.
Live music on Friday night.  Having a pint of chinook a licious.  This is becoming my favorite bar.

luv this place - just might be THE best local brewery. great atmosphere in tap room + dog friendly to boot! luv their germanized names & am continuously amused by their insistence to hoosierize the pronunciation of every one of them ;)
Beer is really good. The staff wad amazing. I got a growler of their Rye IPA. Its a darker IPA and is probably the best IPA I've ever tasted.

Top reasons why I keep coming back to Bier Brewery in no particular order! 

1.A fresh spanking new tap list comes out every Wednesday so there is always something new to try. 

2.If desired, line um up and sample each style. I must warn you this may make it challenging to pick just one. Well played Bier, now I must purchase two growler fills ...not a bad thing!

3.Bier is dog friendly!

4. PDG is so Pretty Darn Good it became my gateway IPA leading me to new hoppy adventures!

5. DFG IPA, Belgian Dubbel, Special K Kolsch 

6. Seasonals - Marzen, Pumpkin Ale, Pumpkin Porter, Chocolate Mint Stout 

7. As a aspiring metalsmith I appreciate the metalwork represented here.

8.Great Fermentations is right around the corner. There you can find extract kits of similar Bier styles to brew at home.  

9.Their beer is consistently exceptional and award winning! In fact, they just won a Silver medal at GABF for their Sanitarium.

So as to not be redundant with all the other great, long reviews people have written, I will keep this short and sweet.

- This is the best beer in town.
- The staff is friendly and go above and beyond to help
- The bathroom was very clean
- They do NOT serve pints here, likely due to our goofy liquor laws, but they happily serve samples of all the styles they have on tap
- The prices for a growler fill ranged from $10 - $14 when I was there on Friday.
- Those prices are totally worth it.

Bier Brewery has made an IPA believer out of my hop-averse husband, so I'm giving them 5 stars! 

We wandered in one weekend in July as part of our "every brewery in Indianapolis" tour (because it's good to have goals, right?) and got samples of all their brews. Unlike a lot of places, you can get a little sample taste of each beer they have on tap gratis. Nice!

They have several permanent beers, as well as rotating taps that change weekly. The IPA, according to my husband, was "not too bitter, and well blended". PDG (Pretty Damn Good) ale definitely lives up to its name, and the Weizengoot has a really nice array of flavors. 

We went home with a growler of the rotating tap IPA (praise the Lord for small miracles!) and a hankering to come back soon for more.

Beer sampling in the 'burbs! What's not to like about that?

Bier Brewery is one of Indy's newer microbreweries situated on the outskirts of town, which is definitely worth the drive and visit. I stopped by about an hour before closing, which was more than enough time to chat with the servers, learn about the brewery and, of course, sample some product. Oh, and the samples (no pints) are free. Woo Hoo! 

Granted, they aren't the typical 3-4 oz., but if your goal (like mine) is to try a little of everything, they were the perfect sampling sizes for nine different pours. Most of the current brews were lighter in color and flavor with nothing on the dark side, although one of the girls told me they can and have brewed up to 100 different varieties and their tap list rotates constantly...what!? Very impressive.

After enjoying their current lineup, I walked around the relaxed tap room, decked out with couches and lounging chairs. Oh, and if you want further proof that Bier is about quality in addition to quantity, make sure you check out their wall of fame, covered in numerous awards and ribbons from various brewing competitions, including the Great American Beer Festival. 

Just like one of their self-proclaimed/named brews, PDG, this place is pretty damn good. 'Nuff said. 4.5 Stars.

Surprisingly, I was not that impressed. I thought it would be amazing based on the reviews. I thought two of their beers on tap were good but the others were very generic. We all liked the mild and the farmgal. There was no description beneath any of the titles on the board so I didn't even realize they had a brown-like at first because it was called a mild and I haven't seen that type before. Not impressed with the plastic cups instead of glass. I might stop by again to give it another chance when they have some new options on tap.

My fiancé and I stopped in here on Saturday afternoon to check this place out. I was very happy we did. We sampled the Belgian Dubbel and liked it enough to get a pint. It was a bit busy while we were in there (there was a brewery crawl making it way through there), but we were able to find a nice place to chat and check out the scene.

Once the crawl cleared out, we sat at the end of one of the long tables and chatted for a bit. The prices are very reasonable, especially if you go the growler route. 

There were a few different beers to try (mint chocolate chip stout comes to mind...) and I would love to come back here and keep sampling, and also to fill a growler. 

The atmosphere is very laid back, with couches, a few high top round tables, and a long family style table with mis-matched chairs. Its charming. 

We will definitely be back to keep trying out some new brews.

Indy has so many great breweries and it helps that they are dog-friendly so you can have your four-legged friends around. Bier is moments from our house and it's a very quaint taproom. It's got your standard board games and you can order food to eat here but I really like the fact that they sell cold beer so you can come in and grab a six pack or mix and match different cans and create your own pack. They also have some wooden carved pieces for sale that are pretty cool to check out. I'm not a huge beer drinking but I like to try different options and I think having a flight of beers would've been pretty cool but they do let you sample at the counter. They have a couple of small tables outside for when it's nice too!

I'm giving this place four stars on account of DFG. I LOVE DFG! I think it's on par with some of 3 Floyds hoppy beers, it's THAT good. If they have it, get it!

I normally stop in on a Friday, and they only let me sample three beers which I think is kind of lame. I also think their name is dumb, and also their slogan is terrible. They NEED better marketing. Whenever I tell someone I stopped by Bier Brewery, they ask me which one (because it just sounds like I stopped by a beer brewery), and then I have to spell their name... annoying! Also, their slogan is "Come taste our awesomeness!" This sounds like something an unoriginal frat bro would think of in three seconds, probably while smashed. You can do better!

I stopped in last Friday, and I brought in a couple growlers, and I tried three of their beers (only three due to their imposed limit). After sampling, the guy behind the bar asked "Do you know what you'll be getting?" It was that awkward moment where I had to reveal that I really didn't like the three samples I had, and would not be getting any. Why not ask "What did you think?" or "Would you like a growler fill?" Just a little annoying, because its not the first time this has happened. If they would have let me sample a few more, I probably would have gotten a growler fill, but I just didn't like the ones I tried.

Again, if it weren't for DFG, this place would have a lower review, but it is just THAT good. :)

Being a beer enthusiast and the only form of alcohol i actually like to drink, i visited all breweries in and around Indy.
This is my favorite brewery of all. They are a small batch brewery and usually do not distribute much in the city of Indy except 5-10 places and that too on and off.
However, their tasting room is absolutely worth a visit. Upon entering you are greeted by a friendly and knowledgeable staff who are more than willing to give you a sample of each of their many creations. Yes, i do call them creations because the way they experiment with beers can only be found in a very few other breweries.
I have been here multiple times to get my growler filled and always get beer from here when my friends are visiting.
I have always found 4-5 that are very good among the 6-10 that they usually sample and i have found out that i am not the only one.
If ever one day i open a brewery of my own i wish for it to be like this. The master brewer is there in person most of the time and the staff is the same.
Great beer and decent prices willing to fill your growlers between Wednesday and Sunday ranging from $10-$24(for the really special brews)

My only suggestion to them is to sell dark glass growlers and get rid of the clear ones.

Definitely a hidden gem in Indy.

I stopped in to pick up a generous donation for a charity auction, lost an hour, sampled beer after beer, learned a ton and walked away with yet another growler to add to the collection. 

I only wish I'd drug friends along to hang on the couches and lose even more time. 

I had the chance to try them again at a fundraiser this weekend (did anyone pick up on the fact that they're giving back to the community all over the friggin' place? AWESOME! ... and thank you!). I enjoyed a big 'ole "Special K" (sounds healthy, right?). It was delightful. Not too thin, but not loud enough to overpower the conversation I was having with friends. Absolutely hit the spot. 

Who wants to go back and drink our way down the line?
Very cool place, well crafted beers. As local and personal as it gets.

I have visited this remarkable brewery numerous times now. I am hooked. Great space. Top notch staff in all aspects of customer service and beer acumen. 

On my last visit I choose the Oranjunkel for my growler fill, but the keg ran out half way through the fill. The fellow allowed me to take that home on the house and gave me a loner growler which I had filled with the coffee porter. 

The fact that they have no true "house" beers is a major draw. The sheer creativity and passion really shines through on each batch and makes being a local beer fan more exciting than ever. The anticipation from week to week is palpable. 

If you are picky on style, it might seem like an inconvenience when they don't have the style you loved on your last visit. Personally, I sampled each beer available and would have been happy no matter what I left with in my growler.  Indy should be proud of such a gem.

Thank the Lord above, good beer in Indy DOES exist. While this place is strictly for tasting, they offer some quality brews that will make it hard for you to pick just one to take home with you (thus the reason I picked three).

My colleague and I wandered in on a Wednesday evening and sidled right up to the bar. We were immediately greeted with a smile and nine tasting cups of their current beer on tap. 

Their options change weekly, but highlights we discovered included their trippel (this one will sneak up on you...but it will be worth it), the saison (very nice for summer), and the Madre (a crisp wheat ale, I believe). 

Bier offers three growler options - the standard glass, a half size plastic version, or the high-priced/high-quality insulated version. Regardless of your choice, they definitely offer well-attenuated awesomeness.

Breweries can reside anywhere. You may drive by Bier Brewery without evening knowing it. Located in an office-like strip mall, Bier Brewery feels like a treasure you've stumbled upon that you want to tell all of your friends about. 

This tap room has over 10 beers on tap constantly, offering growler fills, bullet fills (half a growler) and pints to enjoy. Bier Brewery is just that, though - a tap room with limited seating, no food or other beers available. I'm OK with that - their beer makes up for all the rest. And many times they have food trucks out front to fill your belly with.

I love that they aren't located downtown like many of our other local breweries (but I'll be honest, I love it most because they're convenient for me). I hope that someday they grow enough that they could expand their building - I've been when it was standing room only and barely room to stand at that. But times like those just make me smile, because people drinking great local craft beer are happy people ;)

If you're looking for a great local brewery, then Bier is where you should be. I haven't tasted a single beer yet that I didn't love. Bonus: if they have their Dubbel on tap, then you need to try it :)

GREAT selection of top notch beers! Very educated staff and extremely friendly. It was great to "chat beer" with them.  Growlers are all they do right now, but you do get generous samples.  Growlers look to be about $12 to fill, which is well worth it! I can't wait to see what other great brews they will produce!

I love this place.  I am always delighted to stop by after work.  There are many reasons I always recommend Bier.  

The employees are always friendly and knowledgeable.  The interior is modern and clean.

They let you taste any of the Biers, assuming they are not too busy.  They do growler fills and bullet fills (a half growler, 32oz).  The prices on bullet fills are just half of the regular growler price.  The beer is always good and fresh.  Enjoy a pint while you are here, then take some to go!  I have tried their Weizengoot, PDG, good pils, and the Special K kolsch.  All of these were fantastic!  I also had a tongue punch IPA, which was a limited release brew.

I would definitely recommend Bier to anyone, whether you are just getting into craft beer, interested in craft beer, or a beer geek like me.  There is a Bier for everyone!

Award winning beer served by the nicest people in Indianapolis.  The beer is good and by good I mean GOOOOOOOOD.  Sessie, Special K are my two favorites.  Stop in for a brew and head next door to Movable Feast for lunch.  I am pretty sure they are cool with you walking in with the beer.  They are on tap it seems like everywhere and I think they are now in multiple liquor stores now.  Either way... get your hands on some beer from Beir.   Keep making amazing brews fellas!

The beer at Bier is always delicious!!!! Dark German Hefe is delicious! So cozy whether you want to sit on the very comfy couches or play games at the tables with friends it's a wonderful experience!!!

I heard really good reviews about this place so I had to heck it out. Unfortunately for me it wasn't as good as I was expecting. They did offer a significant selection of beers but it was a very small location. They do allow dogs so maybe if I had a dog it would be better for me!

It seems that each of Indiana's breweries has its own unique experience. Bier is no exception to this rule. I walked in to a small tasting room on a busy Friday evening (they serve pints only on Saturday and some Friday nights). I had never had Bier beer (because brewfests don't always count), so I set out to try several of the beers on tap. 

I was happy to learn that I could try as many samples as I wanted...for FREE. I sampled 5 beers before settling on my choice for a growler fill. I didn't love any of their beers, but I was certainly going to leave with a growler for the night. 

Even though I didn't love their beer, which was more than double the cost of the larger local brewery on a Friday, I'm giving them 4 stars for several reasons: 1) Unlimited sampling, 2) Friendly service, 3) the ability to have a local musician playing in the taproom without making it overwhelmingly loud

This is a great place to get beer, i personally enjoy all of the beers they put out.. and the location is awesome as well, the chalkboard that they decorate for each cycle of beer they put out is really well done! I can't believe that someone does it by hand. They usually have good games on, and that of course changes season to season.. place is dog friendly as well, so it's always cute to see the different pups! Don't forget to play a classic board game, it's awesome to play guess who and enjoy some tasty craft beer

"God, I'd give anything for a drink. I'd give my god-damned soul for just a glass of beer."  - Jack Torrance, The Shining

Fortunately for us, the friendly folks at Bier charge a lot less. 

Make a u-turn right out of the parking lot of those "other" Indianapolis breweries and head to Bier for some of the best craft beer this state has to offer. 

I've been complaining for quite a while about the lack of creativity shown by most breweries around here. The same beers over, and over, and over.  You can throw that tired formula out the window now. These guys are bringing it with much more than the usual IPA, wheat, amber, and porter. 

You like dunkles? How about two different dunkles on draft, one made with rye? Will that work for you? How about a smoked brown, a Belgian pale, or a stout that was recently named the best in the state at a local competition? Oh, cream ale is your thing? Stop on in for a delicious brew that kicks the ass of that "other" cream ale in town. 

A Belgian dark strong is coming soon. Hell yes. 

No pints for sale so you'll have to sample it out and growler it up. Stop in often because the board is constantly changing.

Indiana Sunday beer laws are so stale, yet I still find myself wishing I could purchase on Sunday without going to a sit down restaurant.  Which is why I'm ecstatic about finding the Bier Brewery, and somewhat ashamed I've not written about it before now.  

They have a great selection of brews each week, beginning on Wednesday through Sunday, but have been running out midweek due to their popularity.  If you're unaware, they've won several awards for their suds, one of which being my favorite; Sessie.
  
Staff is knowledgeable and friendly, eager to share information and allow you to sample their current offerings.  I've taken several friends in with me and proudly gifted a friend with their 32 oz. 'Fruit Cocktail' brew, pint glass & sticker to share the love.  

Make a point to get there and judge for yourself.  They'll fill your growlers from other stores and you might just like it so much you'll bump my 'duchess' status ; )

I live incredibly close to this brewery and I FINALLY made my way to its doors. For months, it has been a constant siren song begging me to walk through the doors and drink beer. I gave in. I conquered. This brewery and taproom is fantastic. The people are great, the beer is great, the atmosphere is great, and the merchandise is great. I'm looking forward to buying an Indiana Bier Brewery t-shirt or sweatshirt. They will give you samples of anything you want to try without consequence. They are truly trying to help you find the beer for you. Sample as many or as little as you want until you find your match. I decided on a growler of the DFG pale ale and it was really great. The whole thing, including the first initial purchase of the growler (which you keep) and the beer totaled around $17. It's completely worth while.

Bier Brewery is neat because they hold casual pint nights where people can come and socialize and drink pints of Bier beers. There is a fire pit and all around happiness in singularity in orbit around good beer. If you are on the north east side of Indianapolis, definitely check this place out. It's a perfect place to purchase Sunday beer for when the man holds you down. They will fill any growler. Don't pass it up!

For God so loved the world that he gave them Bier.
 
As a homebrewer and overall beer enthusiast, Bier has become my place of worship.   I moved to Indy a few months ago and visited a few of the local establishment around town looking for a good "fit" - SunKing was cheap and plentiful, Fountain Square Brewing was progressive and unique, 3WiseMen was commercial and accessible, but Bier made me a believer.  

A few sips of the DFG, India Brown Ale, and Chinookalicious was all it took.  The taste, the freshness and the intoxicating aroma of hops were overwhelming.  Their brews are inspiring and experimental, but they never sway from their core values; small batches and quality ingredients.  I left my first visit to Bier with five growlers.  Now that I'm part of the Bier doctrine, I regularly visit on the weekends to make my offerings ($10-$16 per growler) and listen to their employees preach the word of good brew.  

If you have fallen unto troubled times and are looking for guidance, Bier will show you the way.

Really outstanding beer.  I think the best in Indianapolis...and they do take some chances with their products.

More of a "nano" brewery..than "micro"...as their beer is in small batches..which means they may not have what you want for long....also..if you find a beer you like...chances are you won't see it again !  While this poses a bit of a conundrum for a hoppy IPA creature of habit such as moi...it also forces me to try different brews that I might not normally consider....

For instance....

I am not typically fond of Belgian type brews...the yeasts usually give the beer a "bananna-ish" taste....at least according to my taste buds, however..the Belgian here was delicious, smooth, very complex in that there were a bunch of flavors that showed up individually and collectively....just yummy !

I am by no means an expert, and happily quaff the most egregious of macro brews...but the beer here is fantastic.  

Indy has some excellent micro breweries..finally..... .this has to be among the best..if not the best.

Bier has truly amazing beers.  I've been to most breweries in Indiana, and I think that this place has the best beer overall.  They have a great variety, and I really enjoyed the subtle flavors. 

Even the beers that were styles I don't normally like (weisen and smoked) were pretty darn good. 

The only downfall (?) is that I fell in LOVE with the tripel, and it's already out of the rotation.

I had high expectations for Bier since they are such large distributors but their tap room disappointed me. There wasn't much seating so I had to stand to drink since it was busy. I wasn't a fan of their beer selections at that time and haven't been back.

Pointless to expound beyond what has been said so eloquently and with passion by others..

REALLY PHENOMENAL BEER !

This may be the best brewery in Indy!

There is definitely a reason why Bier Brewery has won numerous awards. Their beers are freaking delicious! I don't think I've had one beer from them that I didn't like. The environment it self has such a nice, relaxing, and chill vibe to it. Another yelper described it as homey and I have to agree with that! It's a great place to come hang out with your significant other/friends/family. They also are dog friendly so that is a major plus for me! 

The staff are the friendliest people! My husband and I visited this past weekend and brought our pup with us. There wasn't room outside on their patio so we decided to find a seat inside until something opened up. While we're enjoying our beers, an older gentleman (maybe the owner/manager) came over and talked to us and asked us questions about our pup and even gave her a treat! I thought that was super sweet and our pup definitely appreciated it.

Overall, our experience at Bier was phenomenal and I foresee many, many more visits in the future!

there is not a single think not to like about this place.....just go there and ask them to "set you up" they will pour you samples of all of thier beers.  You cannot drink onsite, but you can buy a growler and take it home with you.

This is this best beer in the state! If you are getting local craft beer come in and check it out.

They have awesome events most days too! Saturday is a great time because they do a comedy night (and it's free.) Definitely, a must do spot in the city.

Bier has great beer,  We made a point to go on Wednesday so we could play some bingo. We arrived at 6:15 had a couple beers while waiting for the bingo to start at 6:30. We hung around until 7:15 but no bingo, we left. I'm relieved our friends decided not to come with us. Not a big deal but don't advertise it if your not going to follow through.

I've been to Bier a few times.  I have always been greeted warmly and the staff is knowledgeable and helpful.  It is nice to sit down and have a pint or get your growlers filled.  I will be back for more bier.

The second Saturday of every month they have a FREE comedy show. It is usually very good and super funny. I would actually pay to see it. Also I think it goes without saying that the beer is the best in Indy or possibly anywhere. Fan forever.

If you can stop by for a tasting, do it. They have over 100 beer recipes, but usually about 12 or so on tap, based on memory. The tasting room is spacious for groups and the wall is adorned with brewing awards. The bartender told me this is the second oldest brewery in Indy next to Sun King.

I am in love! This is my new favorite brew place! The best part about it, the variety! I was lucky to go on a pint night, the vibe was fun, and everyone was there loving these good brews. I go to GABF every year and this is a nice mini taste of a varietal of beers. I had their Kolsch, it was crisp and cold as it should be. I am not always the biggest hoppy fan, but the DFG IPA was clean, light and very fresh tasting. It didn't kill my taste buds as I enjoyed the Pumkin beer (best one I have had all fall and winter) next! 
The hours kind of suck but the fact that next week they will have different beers next week will have me hooked!
Nice bartenders. Bier has good beers made to the style. It's not a spot that does off-the-wall stuff, so don't expect any oddities.

I've always loved Bier brewery.  We've been going here for years!  It's such a cozy place to sit on an afternoon and watch sports, play a game, or sit and talk.  We always bring our dog and they are so accommodating and sweet to him!

My favorite thing to do is order a Wiezengoot and sit on the couches in the middle.  They have great views of the tv and a coffee table to play games on.  I do wish they had food, but I believe they are okay with you ordering food or bringing it with you, not 100% about that though!

Absolutely love this tap room. The fact that the indoor is dog friendly is a major plus for this new puppy mom. And the good beer? That's just another plus! 

Most recently went in on a Friday night, planning to meet a few friends with our pups. I was pleasantly surprised to see just how crowded it was! Barely any room to sit. We got lucky and were able to snag one of the couches though.

Stood in line and got two beers - very happy the pumpkin beer is back! It's a great one, probably my favorite local pumpkin beer. 

We brought our new puppy and he was the bell of the ball in this place. He loved trying to meet some new friends, and although he is small he is not afraid to waltz right up to the big pups. 

Look forward to coming back here many times in the winter!

One thing I absolutely love about this place is the relaxed, casual atmosphere here. Although I don't know many of the regulars here yet, as I myself am not one (yet), I feel as though I could stop by any table on any given night and easily strike up a conversation with the guests. But I couldn't in good conscience write about my love for this place without acknowledging how crazy I am for being a dog friendly establishment. It has been a life saver for socializing our puppy during the winter time. The chalk  art work is always incredible thanks to their resident artist, one of my favorites being her rendition of Hulk Hogan. They have an ample selection of their brews, and good specials throughout the week. Their standby kolsch is always a good go to, but their seasonal never disappoint.

Gotta be my favorite craft beer place in Indy. The tasting room has a nice atmosphere with some couches and bar top tables. There also an outdoor patio out front. Not a huge place. They don't do food, but the quality of the beer definitely makes up for that.  I would stack up their menu of beers up against any others in Indiana hands down. The spend their money on quality, not advertising. Check em out.

This place is so close to my apartment, so I thought I'd give it a shot. They're always around at brew/beer festivals, too! 

I decided to go because I wanted to try the place out, and they also were having free stand up comedy on Friday! 

I can't give this place a full five stars, because it just doesn't have that atmosphere where you feel like you belong or fit in. I think it's partially because it's not as "homey" as some of the other breweries in town. I tried one of their brews, the saison, I believe. It was good, but nothing to write home about. 

Their staff was extremely helpful in getting me and my friend chairs to sit as the comedians were on. It was a good experience, one that will have me coming back some time in the future.

How is it that I have lived in Indy for three years, written copious reviews (for restaurants on Yelp and beers on Untappd) yet not written anything for one of my top breweries, hell, my top businesses in general, in the midwest??!! I should add a disclaimer; I rarely hang out at Bier. I like the people and the atmosphere, but the beer is just too good, and I'm afraid said delicious beer will cause me to drive back home drunk! So, I nearly always get growlers, bullets, and/or cans to go. The mix-and-match cans option is a huge plus because, like Central State and some other local breweries, Bier is good at having a mix of house favorites and new experimental beers in cans at any given time. Standouts include PDG (a perfect pale ale), their ESB (which is unfortunately getting harder and harder to get since it is so coveted), Sabbath (a black Kolsch), last year's Marzen (the best canned Marzen on the planet), their legendary pumpkin ale (the best I've ever had), and a variety of other Belgian-style ales (they don't do exclusively Belgians, I just happen to like Bier's take on Belgians). I haven't even had their most famous beer, Sanitarium, but that's partially because I don't like boozy, barrel-aged beers (and also because it sells out so fast). This is one of the best breweries in Indiana, and likely the whole midwest. No flights, but they'll let you taste until you find something you like (which won't take long if you are a beer lover). They are also really active in the community and do countless fundraisers. I'm down to my last month in Indy, and this will be one of the places I miss the most!

PS: Little known fact: their 2015 (or perhaps 2016) biere de guarde (a French style ale) is in my top three beers of all time, maybe even #2!

It's a little embarrassing the quantity of breweries I have been too. But considering Tyler and I make it a habit to visit one brewery in every city we visit we have developed a little bit of a brewery snobbery. Bier hits all the right notes with us and checks off all the boxes! This place has that neighborhood hangout feel with eclectic seating and a great casual patio. They are dog friendly and the staff are extremely people friendly. When you walk in it can be a little intimidating because everyone else seems to know what they want. But spend two seconds with the staff at the bar and the chalkboard that beautifully displays their current taps and you won't be disappointed. I have not had a bad beer here...ever. So be adventurous and ask for help if you need it. Also they have board games and live music on certain nights so if you want a low key night out this is your place!
Now open on Tuesdays with $8 growler fills. What a deal!!! Dogs are allowed in the beer tasting area. Be sure to sign up for their online newsletter to get the latest scoop and happenings with Bier.

We stumbled upon this little gem off the beaten path about a year ago...and we keep going back.  They keep some of the same types of staples (try the Weizengoot) and rotate in seasonal and special beers too.  We recently had the Pumpkin Ale and the Autumn Saison -- both really tasty.

The initial cost when purchasing your very own growler seems a bit steep, but just remember -- you can bring that dark, curvy, beautiful glass jug back in and fill it with 64oz of delicious liquid courage any time from that day forward... even on Sundays.  Heck -- especially on Sundays in Indiana. 

Rumor has it that they are closed on Mondays and Tuesdays and only offer pints on the weekends.  Maybe we are just lucky and always hit it on a day where pints are available?!?  Also have heard the food trucks are only available when pints are.  Hmmm... I need to buy a lottery ticket with my luck so far! 

A growler refill costs 12-14 bucks, depending on the variety (the Pumpkin is currently $14 while the staples are $12).  The only thing is -- you cannot drink from the growler on site.  They also offer a smaller glass to-go bottle called the "Bullet" (32oz) should 64oz seem a bit much.

Another bonus is that they have had a different food truck parked outside each time we have gone.  They have ranged from gourmet Mac-N-Cheese to Some Guys Pizza (the Greek was uhh-mazing), to comfort food (fried catfish, pulled pork).  A nice addition when the munchies strike and they don't mind if you bring it inside to enjoy with your pint.

There are comfy couches and a TV -- looks and feels like a little community living room in the middle.  There are also tables to sit at and the restrooms are clean.  You can even buy cute/funny TShirts should you choose.

My advice: 
1.  Get your complimentary samples when you arrive -- 3 per person or 6 samples total for 2 people -- so bring a friend and share the wealth.  
2.  Pick a pint to enjoy on site.  
3.  Take a growler to go.  
4.  Repeat.

My favorite brewery in Indy! Bier has a unique coffee-shop atmosphere that makes you feel welcomed as soon as you walk inside. The best part about Bier is that it's dog-friendly, making it my go-to cold weather watering hole. Great to stop by after picking up the dog from Puppy Playground across the street. They've got live music, euchre night, and the best fortune cookies to munch on while you drink. They rotate their taps often and have a little bit of something for everyone. Definitely worth checking out!
One of my favorite brewery and tap rooms in Indy. I love the relaxed atmosphere and that I can bring my dog.

One of my favorite breweries in Indianapolis! They serve great beer all year round (especially during the fall when they bring out the pumpkin ale) that they have something for everyone. The special kolsch and the weizengoot are two of my top faves for year round beer.

The taproom is super welcoming to humans and fur babies and sometimes on Friday nights they have a comedy show that is free to attend. No food here except for some chips and pretzels but you can order in if you would like. No surprise that they have many awards on the wall. Shows they are consistently good. Outdoor area in the summer and plenty of parking. 

I plan to revisit this place often!

I live fairly close to here, but don't come very often. The staff is ok but there have been a couple of times they were hurrying me to make a selection. They do have a good amount of beers to choose from and they taste great.

It was nice to come back to Bier Brewery after a year absence from Covid-19.   Before the pandemic hit, I would come here to Bier Brewery quite often for beer fests and their special release beer events.   Bier Brewery has a wonderful craft beer selection such as their South Simcoe IPA and their PDG pale Ale.   The redrum beer is supposedly very good as well,  but have not tried it yet. The Brewery has been around for quite a while and it is nice to see that they are still going strong during this pandemic.  I look forward to when they start having events again and we can taste their new releases,  because they produce wonderful new beer each year.  The Halloween release beers were the reason to come to Bier Brewery,  so I am hoping this will be resurrected by this next year. It is worth it!!

Love this spot. It's underrated and always low key. Which is my kinda place. Beer is good and staff is always really friendly. They're dog friendly too which is always a bonus. They have free events and everyone is always laid back!
Damn awesome biers. Best brewmaster in town.  Don't let Yelp confuse you. They are open until 9pm T W H.

This was stop one on the Indy Brew Bus Tour, so lucky for you this is the one review where I was completely sober during the experience. I'm not a beer person, so my reviews of breweries are more about the experience than the actual beer. If you're a beer snob, this review may not help you, however, for my occasional beer drinkers out there, I'll be speaking your language.

This brewery has won awards for their beer and they are proud of them. They are displayed around the room, which makes for cool décor. They have a table in the front with all the Big 10 schools' logos carved in individual tree trunks. I always love seeing the Big M - Go Blue!

They had one porter on tap, so I was solid. The options are limited, but what they do, they do well. My total without tip was $5.45. I don't think I'll ever get over the cheapness of beer in Indy. 

They have a ton of seating both inside and outside. We opted to sit outside and stumbled upon the 5280 Bistro Food Truck. It's a neat partnership to have the food truck outside. If you have a chance to eat at it, you should! I love breweries that have food truck partnerships!

Love this dog-friendly tap room! Bier's weekly selection of beers is posted on their website and Facebook and very artistically displayed behind the bar. Their Special Kolsch and seasonal pumpkin beer are two of my favorites! Mixture of soft seating, high tops and large tables - great for any occasion. And if you're lucky, Fancy Fortune Cookies has complimentary fortune cookies on tables. Bier also has pre-packaged snacks available for purchase and the restaurant next door will deliver, too!

Great place to go to get high quality craft beers. You will definitely pay more at Bier than at other craft breweries, but it shows in their quality. Currently, their pumpkin ale is on tap and it is one of the best pumpkins in the Midwest. Sample away while you are there, samples are free. They have also started selling beer by the pint and they have a nifty little outdoor area. Note: They are not open on Monday or Tuesdays.
Great food!  We had the cheese board, brewers wings, stuffed jalapeños, and the mahi-mahi tacos. All were very good!  Staff was very friendly too. We would definitely go back if in the area again.

After seeing and tasting Bier brews on various local tap menus, we visited their 65th street brewery/tap room on a brew bus tour, located about 10 minutes from Broad Ripple.

The tap room has a fun, relaxed vibe and their chalkboard menu is always filled with fun and detailed art (check out their Instagram page to see!).  The tap room is dog friendly and you can bring in your own food as well! (During the day, and until 6pm, try Moveable Feast right next door!)

Lately we've been going every Wednesday for trivia night, when they incidentally also offer $4 pints of all of their beers. They also host some other game nights during the week as well.  Their brewing awards speak for themselves and they have a solid selection and variety of beers for all tastes.

Service is terrible (Carmel location).  We went tonight (at 6:00 pm) with our two children for the first time.  We  walked in and there was no "seat yourself sign".  We waited for a server, but no one came.  Lady bar tender saw us but did not acknowledge us.  My husband walked to the bar and asked if we had to seat ourselves.  She said yes and pointed to the section we had to sit in because we had kids with us.  We sat down and took a couple minutes to look at the menu (very limited) and then went to the bar to order.  The same bar tender lady said "oh, I'm sorry, the kitchen closes at 6"... Wow, you didn't think to tell us this when we came in and had to ask if we needed to seat ourselves (wouldn't that make you realize we had never been here before?).  We will not be coming back and will take our business elsewhere!

Today was my first visit to Bier Brewery. How have I not been here before!?! Such a cool place with great beers on tap. I tried the PDG (American pale ale) and The Metro (session IPA). Both were amazing! 

The atmosphere is relaxed and just a great place to grab a drink with friends. 

I will definitely be returning!!

This is one of my favorite breweries ever.  Whenever I'm in town, I always stop here and it's always a highlight.

They rotate their beer menu, so there is always something new to try and they haven't let me down yet.  I do have my favorite tastes, but I also like to branch out with a brewery that I trust.  

I love the vibe of the tap room.  I must say I am a bit of a Star Wars geek (it's in my heritage from my dad I guess), so I love the decor!

Great place to become a regular or to visit as you're passing through.

Tucked away on a side street right next to Great Fermentations. A really cute place to take your dog(s) and maybe even a date! I forget what it was called, but the last time I came they had a really good amber ale. Unfortunately it doesn't seem like they bottle it, so I settled for their DFG and PFG, both of which are delicious and refreshing AF. 

If you don't come here for the beer (but really why wouldn't you) at least come here for the puppers!

One of the things that makes me most happy about living in Indiana is that there are so many great independent breweries in this fine state. Bier Brewery is one of these great breweries. And I came across it by happenstance: I was assigned to pick up an item that they donated to a fundraiser. (Note: They donate to fundraisers! That automatically elevates them several levels in my mind.) I didn't even know these guys existed prior to this. They're located in a nondescript strip mall near the railroad tracks in a sleepy neighborhood off Allisonville Road. You could easily drive pass them. I almost did!

Anyway, they sell cold beer here, so you can pick up a six pack (or two, or three) on your way home. I grabbed a six pack of their seasonal Dankzilla, a red ale that's citrusy and bitter in the best way possible. They also sell growlers to go. 

I'd like to visit again and enjoy a pint or two while sitting in their fine establishment. I'll have to come back!

I passed by here from the south side and was surprised I had stumbled upon a meeting the staff was just beginning. I was troubled because it was the second time I had stopped by to fill a growler and it isn't often misfortune strikes consecutively.

Luckily, Jerry, one of the employees at Bier shuffled me in the door and was happy to oblige. I was  referred to Bier by a friend who described their beer as the Lamborghini of beers.

Sure enough they were right! I had stopped in to fill a growler of their Pumpkin Ale for a friend...which was good...and ended up getting a growler of their Autumn Saison...which was equally amazing.

The Pumpkin has a rich taste with a very nutmeg finish...the Saison a taste of roasted goodness almost like a perfect cup of coffee.  To put it plainly, these beers are good'er than hell.

Anyone who reads this should give them a try, I highly recommend them and will go back for sure!

I've been to a lot of breweries and a lot of taprooms and I can say that this may in fact be my favorite one. I love walking into what can sometimes be calming atmosphere and sometimes a loud, fun atmosphere. There is a somewhat homey feeling to it with the large couches and wooden tables and chairs. When it is full, you will usually end up sitting next to someone you've never met, which makes it great because you are all there for the same reason: BEER! and usually can start some conversation.

Now lets get to the beer. I have not had a beer there that I did not like. From the PDG to the ESB, the Kolsch and the Weizengoot, it is all great. Wednesdays are pint night, and they have euchre night on Thursdays. One of the best parts is that you can bring your dog. We were a little unsure of bringing ours until we walked in and found 5 or 6 others in there all enjoying this selves. It's a great place for the whole family (adults and dogs, no kids obvs since it's Indiana).This place is a must for anyone big into craft beer.

Pints served on Fridays and Saturdays!
Otherwise, this is a tasting place only. 

We came by on a Saturday -- the Saturday before St. Patrick's Day to be exact. How brave of us! There were party buses out front, but we were not deterred. The space is nice and has plenty of walkway room and some seating, so it never felt packed. The brewery was well-staffed so we didn't wait long before our tastes. 

It isn't the kind of place you want to go and hang out for a LONG time, but it's a nice stop through for something to do one afternoon and to sample and buy some bullets of Indiana suds.

So, full disclosure, I haven't visited the tap room in person, but have enjoyed many of Bier Brewery's creations at events and in cans!  With the ongoing covid 19 pandemic, I'm enjoying food and beverages from local businesses at home these days.    I enjoyed a PDG pale ale with takeout fried chicken tonight and had an amazing meal.  It's a good hoppy selection but isn't jumping on the bandwagon of "extreme hoppiness" if that makes any sense.   In other words, it won't overwhelm food.    They carry the PDG at Market District if anyone is looking for it.    I really do hope to visit in person once this way too long pandemic is under better control!

I met a friend here for a meeting last week after work. I have to admit, I thought this was another place (on Binford) and got a little confused, and didn't even know this place was here. Sure, I've heard of Bier Brewery before and I have had their beer at other places, but this was my first trip to the brewery.
