The environment inside the place is a little outdated. It's a weird mix of like...ocean themed stuff and then also a fancy restaurant. It's a little weird but everything is clean and in good repair and it's never loud or bright in there so it'd be a great place to take a date.

Overall I cannot recommend this place enough. The only thing is I wish we lived closer like we used to so we could go back to being "regulars"!

Had the worst experience here tonight! Maybe the servers were in a bad mood, but Tiwi was completely rude to the entire table from beginning to end. To start with we got the $3 sake, which was absolutely disgusting. Definitely skip if coming on a Wednesday. We ordered the spicy girl roll, salmon avocado roll, and vegetable pad thai. The sushi was good, but the spicy girl roll had a piece of plastic in it. The vegetable pad thai was horrible. The smell of it put us off food so much we had to have it removed from the table. To her credit, Tiwi removed the pad thai from the bill, however was very rude throughout the entire exchange. Will not be coming back.

This place is my boyfriend and I's most favorite sushi and hibachi place to dine. Their clear soup is delicious and their house salad is simple and refreshing. The staff is always friendly and people are always coming by to refresh your drink. 

To the eats: One of my stand-by rolls is the Spicy Girl roll. It is so delicious, with spicy salmon on the inside and spicy tuna mix with crunchy bits on the top. The thing that makes Tomo's sushi so delicious is the plating with the 4 sauces. They pretty much enhance any roll you order. We have tried most of the "special" rolls menu, and alongside the Spicy Girl, the Tomo Special Roll and Keystone Roll are favorites. I prefer to order a side of sashimi on the side, and their salmon sashimi is always fresh, ice cold, and delicious. Seems simple, but it can be easy to mess up sashimi. If you are looking for a smaller roller, I suggest the yellowtail scallion roll or the spicy scallop roll. Both are great.

As for hibachi, their prices are great compared to other places and you get a heaping plate of food that almost always winds up in a "To Go" box. I have ordered the shrimp, chicken, steak, and scallops. None of them disappointed. Their fried rice is some of the best I've had. It is full of flavor and absolutely delicious. Their lunch hibachi specials are extremely affordable.

Two of my favorite details though are the hot towel you are presented with when you are seated, and the sliced orange or candy you are presented with at the end of the meal.

The sushi roll here was okay, and I think it tasted better then the sashimi plate. The spicy scallop hand roll kind of had too much rice in it and not enough scallops that was kind of minced anyway. The edamame tasted like its typical dish. The only plate that I think looked kind of cool was the volcano plate because it had a really cool blue fire flame on the plate which after a minute of sitting on the table in front of us eventually faded off. It you like aesthetics then the volcano plate would be a good choice. Free refills on sodas too. There's also a full bar in this restaurant as well.

Tasty! I've been hearing friends recommend this place for ages, and finally got there myself last Friday night around 8 p.m. We were seated immediately at one of the hibachi tables, and service was outstanding.

Tomo seems to fly a bit under the radar in its strip mall location in front of Walmart, but don't let that deter you. It's much bigger inside than I expected. Hibachi dining seems to be the big attraction here, with all the usual pomp and ceremony --- chefs balancing eggs on their spatulas, creating flaming onion volcanos, tossing pieces of veg into customers' mouths, etc., but the sushi is worth considering as well. There's a pretty extensive menu here, and I really enjoyed my deep-fried spicy tuna "Keystone" rolls. Also sampled some of the hibachi fare, and found the steak, fried rice and veg very good. Ditto the pork gyoza and the edamame. My son is a HUGE fan of the soup and happy to visit just for that alone.

All in all, a great meal. Prices seem reasonable and everything I tasted was very good. And, they give you a $6 off coupon to use if you come back within a few weeks. Which I will.

It's been a few years since I have eaten at Tomo. Always thought the sushi was decent and fresh. A few nights ago I craved sushi and saw Tomo on Door Dash. Verdict is that I feel the same - a decent restaurant. 

We had the veggie tempura, sweet potato roll, tuna roll and Tomo Special roll. Those four items were plenty for me and my husband. Even has a few leftovers. 

Our order was made quickly on a Monday night. Thank goodness there are restaurants open on Mondays. So many are not.

Took my husband here for Valentines dinner...man..please don't go here! If I could give 0 stars I would..I order the soft crab don't do it! Awful..we never got our soup and salad until it was time to go..so it's a carry out at this point..the eggs were burned and the manager is bait shit crazybecause i complained oh..wait..18% gr. if you sat at hibachi tables. The soda was flat..the water taste better..just don't go!

Really good food and service. One of my favorite restaurants in Indianapolis. The prices are fair and there's a hibachi option I've never tried it but it looks entertaining. A good idea for a birthday party or get together.

Genuinely friendly and fun hibachi chefs! Excellent food. Calamari app which can be chewy if not cooked properly or served quick enough WAS PERFECT!
Had a great birthday dinner with friends and looking froward to coming back.

Went for the sushi lunch special! The price was great and the sushi was delicious. It's a little bit dark inside but not too bad. They also did not accept the edamame coupon through Yelp. I would go back though for the great prices and good sushi!

Went here for lunch, sat at the hibachi grill. Lunch special is very affordable and good portion size. $13.50 for filet mignon. Ordered 2 sushi role for $9. Sushi here is just okay. Would return for hibachi.

We had a hibachi lunch here on a Saturday afternoon. I had the chicken hibachi and it was good. Nice portion sizes, lots of food. My only negative is the amount of crowd participation the chef demands. I don't care for the spraying sake and water at people while I'm dinner!  I'm sure it's a personal preference but I'd prefer to just be a spectator not part of the performance.
Great sashimi, generous size pieces and amount. Fresh, love the presentation and everyone is nice!

Really fun experience and food! We went for lunch and got in right away, our waitress was super fast and attentive! We all got hibachi dinners, which is the grill they make food on in front of you. They chef went table by table. So we shared our table with 3 other people but it was fine. We all got soup and salad that comes with the meal. The soup is a mushroom like broth soup and the salad is pretty ordinary with a sesame seed like of creamy dressing. It was good. Then then our chef he, he asked everyone what they got then prepared first rice, then steak/chicken then seafood and then veggies. My family and I waited until he cooked all our stuff f eat while the other group ate as he cooked. So totally up to the person, but just an FYI that you won't revive your food all at once since he's cooking it in separate sections. But all in all fun experience and good food!

I really like this place. My fiance and I go here when we want predictable sushi. Nothing glamorous, nothing too over the top, just good food. I would recommend this to the novice sushi eater or a family. Its a nice atmoshere and everything about it meets expectations.
Doesn't look to fancy from the outside, but the food was great and it was very good service as well. Good place if you want habachi!
I have eaten here several times. Food is good service is great. The staff is very accommodating. Think I will have lunch there today!

We came here on a Thursday night for dinner and the restaurant was packed- however, our friends who have been here before said it was way busier than usual. It took awhile to be seated (30 ish minutes) but after we were seated, it felt like it took our server at least 10 minutes to come see us. Everything was slow... I feel like they were understaffed and not expecting a rush. My meal came out probably 7 minutes before the last meal came out. I had the chicken hibachi dinner- the salad was delicious, the rice was not very flavorful, but I enjoyed the veggies and chicken. We didn't sit at the hibachi tables but I wonder if that experience and having fresh food all cooked at once for the entire table would have made for a better experience.

Yelp has an offer if you check in for complimentary edamame - we showed this to our server but never got the appetizer. Still wondering what happened to that....

Overall, decent food and price for a hibachi/sushi restaurant.

Tomo is located in the corner of a tiny strip mall in front of Walmart. It's front may serve as a disguise, but once you walk in - it has this dimly-lit, upscale atmosphere. Waitresses are nicely dressed in suit complete with a tie. If you are a guy, I guess it makes nice eye candy. Ha. Don't let the looks deter you since it's quite affordable. It's not some half-assed, gross sushi made by an amateur. 

For lunch, $11.95 can get me 3 rolls + a nice size side salad. I got the spicy yellowtail, tuna avocado, and eel tempura roll. They sure are generous with the fish and it tastes fresh like the sea, not the sewage they feed you at cheapo-buffets. It'd be perfect if they had a low-sodium soy sauce, since the regular one they have is quite salty.

Next time, I'll get 2 rolls instead. My eyes were definitely bigger than my stomach since I walked in hungry. I don't want to walk out looking like I have a preggo belly after that rice swells and fills me up. 

Definitely go hit up their lunch specials when you want a healthier alternative from the usual fast food. They have vegetable sushi options for the non-meat eaters as well!

Thought I'd finally give Tomo's a try. My verdict - average. Price wise, Sim still on the fence. I get a better overall taste for a better price, at another hibachi grill place. There was not anything that was "ohh wee tasty" I had the hibachi steak lunch special, that came with a clear soup or salad. I opted for the clear soup, and ordered a Kani salad to accompany my meal. 

Probably will be a minute before I order from here again. I guess I was expecting more of a taste wow than I got. Not saying it was nasty; just that I've had better.

My husband and I love this place. You can never go wrong with Hibachi, but their sushi is the best sushi in the city! The presentation of their specialty rolls is always so pretty! The service is great whenever we go.

A couple years ago, I actually purchased a Tomo Gift Certificate for a friend largely on the recommendation of a friend who'd felt like the person I was buying for would appreciate their sushi options. Despite having never been there myself, I went in and purchased the gift certificate and found myself impressed by the friendliness and atmosphere. 

Flash forward to last night when I met fellow Yelpers Rick G. and Holly G. for dinner after what had been a mentally draining day for all of us due to different reasons. We wanted to hang out together, enjoy a good meal, soak in a decent atmosphere and not have to be "on." 

Mission accomplished. 

I'm not a sushi guy and I can even say that Japanese is not really my favorite type of cuisine. However, I don't "dislike" it and occasionally find that it really hits the spot. I arrived last night at the strip center spot it's located at - a former Discount Video in an area that is kind of hit-and-miss. I already knew that their curb cut at the end of the sidewalk closest to Tomo isn't even close to ADA compliant. It's a steep grade and if you have any upper body issues, there's no way you'll make it up it. I'm fairly decent in terms of upper body strength and even I have to get a bit of a good start to make it up without wheeling backward. 

Once you go in, you have a small entry way and then an entrance that leads to a Hibachi area to the left and a traditional dining room on the right. Tomo also recently started offering online ordering via their website and they also offer delivery. 

Due to a delay at their homestead, Rick and Holly arrived a bit late and after waiting in my car for a few minutes I decided to go ahead and hang out inside. You really get a sense of the ambience as it gets dark outside - the restaurant is dimly lit and the hibachi area was quite lively last night. One table, in particular, seemed to be having way too much fun and I was way impressed with one area that had the flames really going higher than I've seen for hibachi. It was fun to watch even though we were in the more traditional dining room. 

We sat at a 4-top. The server was friendly and attentive. I'd had my first iced tea refill even before Rick and Holly arrived, while I perused the menu. Rick had recent posted a photo of their Katsu Don, a "breaded pork or chicken cutlet deep-fried onion carrot & egg over rice." After considering a Teriyaki dish, I went with the Katsu Don and chose pork over chicken. The arriving dish was far more substantial and looked somewhat different than I'd seen in Rick's photo, though we all agreed it was likely the difference between a lunch special and dinner. This was Rick and Holly's first time being there for dinner. 

The food was quite good - I would likely order it again, though I will confess that Rick's dish looked even better and I think I might experiment a bit. My dish was definitely more than I could eat - somewhat rare for me, and I ended up bring some home. 

This was the definitive 4-star experience for me. The food was very good, the atmosphere quite enjoyable (and way better than you'd expect looking at the strip center), and the service was top notch. The prices are definitely higher for dinner - Rick and Holly ended up surprising me by picking up the bill ("We have a coupon!"), but they seemed to be happy with the value. 

Overall, I wouldn't say Tomo will be a regular spot for me but it's definitely a place I won't hesitate to return to and I wouldn't be surprised if it ends up on my "once in a while" rotation. I will also note that they have lunch specials that are incredibly affordable if you want to give them a try and have a lesser commitment.

Man i feel terrible for not having reviewed this place sooner. Ive been greedy, holding out on you guys. We have been regulars here for the last year or so and hands down if you want delicious huge rolls of sushi that wont leave your wallet empty try this place.

Its has a really nice mix of authentic meals and american friendly dishes that will please your entire party. The menu is huge come try it, you WILL find something you like.

Bottom line best bang for your bucks are....

Sushi: keystone roll....so good
Rice dish: salmon tempura don buri....rice soaked in a sweet and salty sauce with mixed vegetables and eggs. If you likethe flavor of teriyaki, you will love this!
Dessert: green tea tempura ice cream...fried ice cream...need not say more
I normally love this place but last night had a Door Dash delivery. I ordered Shrimp Yaki Soba. It was NOT Soba noodles but spaghetti noodles. Dinner ruined.

What a fun night out! This place is pretty unassuming from the outside, however I was presently surprised with tasty food, good drinks, and great entertainment! 

We came to Tomo for a birthday dinner and celebrated in style with lots of Sake to go around for the birthday boy and all of his guests. 

Another perk- festive fun drink specials! Hello $5!

I went here with some work peeps for a going away party for me. Little side note: we did call and make a reservation. However, we are nurses. We always make reservations around 7:30-8:00 ish, that way people can some after work. So. This apparently threw them off big time at Tomo. They are one of those "seat you when your party is here" places, which I understand, having worked in restaurants for most of my adult life. HOWEVER, we kept trying to explain that 1. we were reducing our party size from the original reservation; 2. people would be coming later. We picked this place for mulitple reasons: because I love sushi; they also have habachi for those people who don't like sushi; and I had never been there (I'm all about a new place). So four to five of us are there at first. We tried to explain that we wanted to be seated, and that more people would be coming later. OMG. First, we had a bit of a language barrier thing going on, and then there is the policy of only seating if the whole party is there. And they could not understand that some of us wanted 
sushi, and some wanted habachi. They kept telling us that they could only seat two or more people for the habachi. For the love, people. We seriously had to explain this to three people. We could not possibly be the vrey first people to ever go there and have this situation. This is not difficult. Seat us all at the damn habachi, already!!!!!! Finally I think we just pretended like the other people weren't coming so they would seat us. It was a bit on the ridiculous side. And they were not busy, to just add insult to injury. 
On to the food. It was seriously delicious. Almost all of us ended up getting habachi AND sushi. Yes, we totally pigged out. They also had a very good drink special-it was fairly cheap and good; $3 for a mai tai, I believe. The sushi was very fresh, and tasted good. The habachi was entertaining. I had the chicken and steak combo habachi. As at all habachi restaurants, the rice was delish!!! 
Now, I do have to say that they gave us a free dessert for my going away. We got some ice creams(their choice). 
Besides the inital fiasco, the staff was very friendly.
Food is too salty... chief seems doesn't have a clue about what he is cooking. No matter what type of food it is, he always put down the same source. Not recommending.

There's definitely some potential here. Sadly, I didn't get sushi this time. The hubs and I are watching our calorie intake for beach season, so we split a hibachi combo. There's a couple combo options, but we went for the filet and chicken. The combo comes with veggies, fried rice and a side soup & salad. To even it up, we ordered an extra side soup & salad. My usual hot green tea was actually more like room temperature. Bummer. 

The plate that our combo came out on was heart-shaped! Our maybe it was shaped like a leaf? Whatev. I'm going with the heart idea. Of course, they brought us extra plates, but I like to share the plate. I feel like it says, "I trust that you won't eat it all." We left only spending about $35 for everything. Not bad.

I may stop in for sushi one day, but I wouldn't go out of my way to get it here. But hey, I could be wrong.

Dinner and a show!  The hibachi section of this restaurant is the only place I have eaten, but they do have a few non-hibachi tables available as well. If you haven't been to a hibachi place before, you are seated around a large grill and your food is made right in front of you. The food is high average, but the experience makes it a fun-out of the ordinary dinner. 

Portions are huge, and come with soup and salad. Bring your appetite. Recommend having this be your only ddestinatoon of the night because you will leave smelling heavily of the food...seriously I can always smell it in my hair after. Tomo has a yelp  check in promo  which was a nice bonus and surprise. 

I have never had a long wait, they do a great job of turning over tables and trying to get you seated. Overall fun experience for a once in a while meal.

Tomo is pretty great! Service is sometimes shaky depending on how you get but the food is almost always phenom! I'm not always a fan of the whole Hibachi experience, open flames, oil, my face, hair and overall life at risk...I'll pass. But this time I arrived with friends who were first timers so they wanted the experience. 

Pro-tip: check in so you can get the free Edamame! I knew I wasn't a fan of edamame but they'd never tried it so we checked in and shared it with the family sitting next to us. 

I did order my regular starter the shrimp cucumber roll add avocado with a side of eel sauce. Which was absolutely amazing so amazing in fact that I did not share with said friends who were present at the table. Just silently sat there annihilating my sushi roll. I did switch up my entree order and tried their Pad Thai which was absolutely fantastic and shared amongst friends (I have some humanity and this was way too good to not spread the wealth)! It was sweet and salty and just overall a piping hot dish of deliciousness! It such a large helping that I had plenty of leftovers that I took home with me and my Wife ate it ALL in the night! #Marriage am I right or am I right? But the good news for you dear reader is that she also loved it so you have 2 thumbs up from us!

Tomo is not an authentic Japanese restaurant but it stays true to the Japanese steakhouse motif. Tomo is great for dinner but their lunch menu leaves a lot to be desired. The dinner Teppanyaki is wonderful with the shrimp being the best part. It's much better than Benihana. The lunch portions are smaller and lack the sizzle present in the dinner food.
They are so rude on the phone sounds like I am forcing them to make reservation she didn't even say thank you or have a good day
